<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is flight time calculated?", answer: "Flight time is calculated as the great-circle distance between two coordinates divided by the aircraft's cruise speed, plus taxi and ground time. This calculator uses the Haversine formula to compute the great-circle distance between the start and end coordinates, divides by the cruise speed you select, and adds a taxi time to approximate total gate-to-gate duration. The result is a rough estimate: real flight times also depend on winds, air traffic control routing, weather diversions, holding patterns, and approach procedures." },
  { question: "Why is my real flight time different?", answer: "Several factors cause real flight times to differ from the theoretical great-circle time. Winds are the biggest factor: headwinds slow you down, tailwinds speed you up, and the jet stream can add or subtract over an hour on a transatlantic flight. Air traffic control routing often requires longer paths than the great circle. Weather diversions, traffic delays, holds at busy airports, and approach patterns all add time. And gate time, taxi time, and boarding are rarely included in published flight times. For real planning, check a live flight tracker for historical durations on your specific route." },
  { question: "What cruise speeds should I use?", answer: "Typical cruise speeds for common aircraft classes: commercial jet (Boeing 737, Airbus A320, etc.) ~900 km/h (485 kn), large wide-body (Boeing 777, Airbus A350) ~900 km/h, regional jet (Embraer E-jets, CRJ) ~780 km/h, turboprop (ATR 72, Dash 8) ~520 km/h, private jet (Gulfstream, Citation) ~780 to 900 km/h, Cessna 172 ~230 km/h, typical helicopter ~260 km/h. Cruise speed is lower than max speed; aircraft trade speed for fuel efficiency during cruise." },
  { question: "Does it include taxi time?", answer: "Yes. The calculator adds a default taxi time of 20 minutes, which is typical for most commercial airports — about 10 minutes for push-back and taxi out, plus 10 minutes for taxi in and gate arrival. Busy hubs can add 30 minutes or more. You can adjust the taxi time to match the airport if you know it. Small general aviation airports often have under 5 minutes of taxi time, while hubs like JFK or Heathrow can exceed 45 minutes during peak periods." },
  { question: "Is great-circle distance accurate enough?", answer: "Great-circle distance is the minimum distance a flight can cover, and is usually within a few percent of the real flight distance. For long-haul transoceanic flights, the difference between the great-circle route and the actual flown route is typically under 3 percent, dominated by wind-optimal routing. For short-haul flights under an hour, the difference is negligible. Use this calculator as a planning tool, not a precise flight time oracle." }
]) %>

